1. Integration Tests

The purpose of these tests are to ensure that you do not break any contracts between downstream and/or upstream components your application integrates
with. You should ensure that all integration points are tested. They are performed against the real downstream/upstream components in integration
environment called int that we have separately created by replicating the production environment. We are not using stubs here.


-------------------------------------------------------
2. difference between unit test and functional test.

unit test- we are not deploying the app in any env, application doesnt even run locally, they dont depend on app to run, stubbed downstream
functional- application needs to be deployed and run, stubbed downstream
integration- real downstream

functional testing checks the software's functionality from the user's perspective,
while unit testing checks the software's internal workings from the developer's perspective.

Functional testing is a black-box technique that does not require access to the source code, means testing by calling application endpoints
while unit testing is a white-box technique that requires access to the source code, means testing by running the test code

we never run app on jenkins slave, we run unit tests on it.

Functional testing is usually done by testers, while unit testing is usually done by developers.
Functional testing is performed during the level of application testing, while unit testing is performed during the software development cycle.

Functional testing has lower number of test cases, higher cost and maintenance, and slower speed than unit testing.
Functional testing helps to find defects in the functionality, while unit testing helps to find bugs in the code. Â¹Â²

