3. difference between acceptance test and functional test.

No, acceptance testing and functional testing are not the same. They have different purposes, scopes, and audiences. ðŸ˜Š

Acceptance testing is a validation activity that checks whether the software meets the customer's needs and expectations. It is usually done by the customer or a representative of the customer,
such as a product owner. Acceptance testing focuses on the end-user's perspective and the business requirements. It is performed on a production-like environment and uses realistic scenarios and
 data. Acceptance testing helps to ensure that the software is fit for use and ready for delivery. Â¹Â²

 We are not doing acceptance testing in njp as all our apps are middleware applications.

Functional testing is a verification activity that checks whether the software performs the functions that it is supposed to do. It is usually done by the developers or testers of the software.
 Functional testing focuses on the software's perspective and the technical specifications. It is performed on various levels of testing, such as unit, integration, system, and regression.
 It uses test cases that cover all the possible inputs, outputs, and behaviors of the software. Functional testing helps to find defects and errors in the software's functionality. Â¹Â²

I hope this answer helps you understand the difference between acceptance testing and functional testing. If you want to learn more about these testing types, you can read [this article](^1^) or [this question](^2^). If you have any other questions, feel free to ask me. ðŸ˜Š

